Introduction
This talk is a bit spontaneous, so author asks for audience's forgiveness in advance.
Neither did I plan to talk here, nor was I doing a lot of math last year - due to the potentially scheduled end of world my focus moved to the more material planes of existence.
Therefore, it will only recast what I know in a form appropriate for the supremely learned audience; maybe adding one or two questions which haunted me during my journey through the Algebra of the Infrared - with the hope of maybe being useful to people currently capable and more adept in abstract matters.
Author would like to thank Andrei Losev for initiating this line of research, Mikhail Kapranov for countless hours of discussions and actually explaining me some parts of the bigger picture, and Gregory Moore for inviting me to speak here.
With that being said, let's start; but not before publicly denouncing the war of aggression and encouraging everyone to try to change the world for better.

Closing remarks
One could even go further and potentially suggest to do the same for surfaces in complex varieties - creating the equation of "closest to the complex subsurface" inside of an almost complex variety. This, however, is a pure speculation already.

13.html.body:
Closing remarks
Another unsettling question, unrelated to the talk but related to AoI, is the fact that we still do not understand what is the differential-geometric meaning of the Schober.
While formally we can say that it categorifies D-modules, this correspondence is largely formal, as it actually categorifies perverse sheaves.
The situation becomes even stranger with AoI construction describing some sort of "Fourier transform", but in the categorified language of perverse sheaves.

I claim, that while it might be hard, one should probably aim to understand differential-geometric notion of 2-connection / 2-D-module. My reasoning for this is twofold:
First of all, mirror correspondence and Dubrovin's conjectures strongly suggest that relative Fukaya category should correspond to the triangulated category of the mirror Fano manifold. However, on the algebraic side the corresponding D-module (which is supposed to be categorified) is given in terms of differential equations, in differential-geometric terms.
Second (and maybe naive) reasoning is the fact that Gauss-Manin connection is not, actually, flat: its curvature is exact.
I will leave this question hanging; personally I feel it should be the most interesting part here, but what do I know.

11.html.body:
Closing remarks
One of the big obstacles in even approaching the original goal of Andrei's program is the fact that the notion of complex surface is unstable, in particular, there are no surfaces in a generic almost-complex manifold.
Similar situation is observed with a pair of vector fields: in particular, if we deform them in a generic fashion, the notion of a leaf ceases to exists.
However, interestingly, the formal combinatorial nature of this problem appears to not be wild, on the contrary, it completely mimics GMW, which is a well posed problem on an elliptic equation.
I would like to suggest that actually we might be able to "choose a gauge" - instead of considering the (functional) equation dXâˆ’v1dx1âˆ’v2dx2=0dX - v_1 dx_1 - v_2 dx_2 = 0dXâˆ’v1â€‹dx1â€‹âˆ’v2â€‹dx2â€‹=0, we should consider the equation of second order measuring leaves that minimize "non-integrability" (I'm not sure what is the exact form of such action, but it is clear that it must exist).
Then, in case of commuting vector fields, the space of solutions will be the same, but the problem will become well-posed.
Moreover, Mikhail Kapranov has shown me the argument that reconstructs the flat structure on the solution of GMW problem XXX from its image. If similar argument is available for such an elliptic equation I propose, then the combinatorics of the AoI will also likely survive.

Motivation: Andrei Losev's program of 2-dimensional enumerative geometry.
Main topic of the talk: combinatorial nature of this problem is completely analogous to AoI despite them being two completely different geometric settings.
Status of the results: typically, they involve only formal counting of the dimensions. There is no "generic position" property to make these results truly geometric yet.

2-Morse theory
Sadly, I do not have the proof for this conjecture (barring obvious cases like RPn\mathbb{RP}_nRPnâ€‹), but there is a certain evidence for this.
Claim: consider the manifold QQQ with angles, and a gradient vector field vvv on it, preserving the stratification. Then, (normal) Morse theory on this manifold should only count critical points that are attractive along the direction transverse to the stratum the reside in.
How to prove the claim: check by local analysis that the topology of the set {f(x)t}\{f(x) {f(x)t} does not change while passing through all other points.
Observation: In case where QQQ is the gradient trajectories of v1v_1v1â€‹ on MMM, and vvv is an action of v2v_2v2â€‹ on this space, the concave paths correspond exactly to the critical points described above.
Observation 2: Moreover, the component of Ï•\phiÏ• living in Hom(g+,g+)\text{Hom}(\mathfrak{g}^+, \mathfrak{g}^+)Hom(g+,g+) clearly corresponds to the standard definition of Morse differential.

Question: How to morph this (clear, but informal) evidence in a full proof? A lot of details seem to be missing.
Question 2: Is there a geometric meaning to the action of the braid group on this category? Is there a sheaf corresponding to the combinatorial Schober data anywhere?

2-Morse theory
Natural question: in GMW, it is shown that g\mathfrak{g}g is a model of Hochschild cohomology of the algebra of concave paths in AAA (it is denoted gâˆž\mathfrak{g^{\infty}}gâˆž in the work of Kontsevich, Kapranov and Soibelman but I will denote it g+\mathfrak{g}^+g+).
Moreover, deformation of g+\mathfrak{g}^+g+ using MC element Ï•\phiÏ• corresponds to the relative Fukaya category.
Question: what is the geometric sense of this deformation in 222-Morse?
Conjecture: it is a category with exceptional collection corresponding to the critical points (of field v1v_1v1â€‹), and morphisms Hom(pi,pj)\text{Hom}(p_i, p_j)Hom(piâ€‹,pjâ€‹) for ijiij realized as singular chains of the space of (possibly degenerate) trajectories of v1v_1v1â€‹ between iii and jjj.
I will refer to this as "Morse category" in what follows.
So, ideologically I expect that 222-Morse theory in some sense uses second field (v2v_2v2â€‹) to find a combinatorial / cellular structure on the spaces of trajectories of the first field.
